                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d673">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.115/1197: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Substance]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-10-07T10:00:00+09:00"
                            >October 7, 1941—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 8—6:38 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1577. Reference is made to the Embassy’s note of August 6 on Japanese
                    interference with American business firms at Chefoo.</p>
                <p>Replying to these representations, the Japanese Foreign Office in a note of
                    October 3, 1941, states that the safeguarding of American property from
                    elements, including Communists, seeking to disturb relations, was the purpose of
                    the measures instituted; that an understanding had been arrived at with the
                    firms concerned in advance; that upon restoration of normal conditions the
                    guards will be removed; and that there were no detentions of nationals of third
                    Powers and their Chinese employes.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
